💻 5. Java Example (Simple MapReduce)

Let’s implement word count

Step 1: Input
List<String> data = List.of(
    "hello world",
    "hello java",
    "world of java"
);
Step 2: Map Phase
Map<String, List<Integer>> mapped = new HashMap<>();

for (String line : data) {
    String[] words = line.split(" ");

    for (String word : words) {
        mapped.computeIfAbsent(word, k -> new ArrayList<>()).add(1);
    }
}
Step 3: Reduce Phase
Map<String, Integer> reduced = new HashMap<>();

for (Map.Entry<String, List<Integer>> entry : mapped.entrySet()) {
    int sum = entry.getValue().stream().mapToInt(i -> i).sum();
    reduced.put(entry.getKey(), sum);
}
✅ Output
hello → 2
world → 2
java → 2
of → 1

⚡ 6. Java Streams = MapReduce

👉 You already use MapReduce daily without realizing it

💻 Example
List<String> words = List.of("hello", "world", "hello");

Map<String, Long> result =
    words.stream()
         .collect(Collectors.groupingBy(w -> w, Collectors.counting()));

👉 Internally:

map() → transform
groupingBy() → shuffle
counting() → reduce

🔥 7. Parallel MapReduce (Important)
Map<String, Long> result =
    words.parallelStream()
         .collect(Collectors.groupingBy(w -> w, Collectors.counting()));

👉 Runs across multiple CPU cores

